{"parse":{"title":"Verb displacement","pageid":31896902,"revid":741154768,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Verb displacement</b> as it relates to prose, is a technique used to impart a lyrical or poetic feel to a phrase, sentence, or paragraph.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> This technique finds particular expression in <a href=\"/wiki/Minimalist\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Minimalist\">minimalist</a> literature. \n</p><p>Specifically, verb displacement involves only those verbs that can be displaced by the word \"is\" or its past tense \"was.\" For instance, in this excerpt from the novel <i><a href=\"/wiki/For_Whom_the_Bell_Tolls\" title=\"For Whom the Bell Tolls\">For Whom the Bell Tolls</a></i>, instead of writing \"He died in April,\" <a href=\"/wiki/Ernest_Hemingway\" title=\"Ernest Hemingway\">Ernest Hemingway</a> displaces the verb \"died\" with \"is,\" and thereby creates a more lyrical effect:\n</p>\n<style data-mw-deduplicate=\"TemplateStyles:r856303468\">.mw-parser-output .templatequote{overflow:hidden;margin:1em 0;padding:0 40px}.mw-parser-output .templatequote .templatequotecite{line-height:1.5em;text-align:left;padding-left:1.6em;margin-top:0}</style><blockquote class=\"templatequote\"><p>\"Kashkin,\" Robert Jordan said. \"That would be Kashkin.\"</p><div style=\"clear:both;\"></div>\n<div style=\"clear:both;\"></div><p>\n\"Yes,\" said Pablo. \"It was a very rare name. Something like that. What became of him?\"</p><div style=\"clear:both;\"></div>\n<div style=\"clear:both;\"></div>\n<p><i>\"He is dead since April.\"</i></p><div class=\"templatequotecite\">\u2014&#8201;<cite><i><a href=\"/wiki/For_Whom_the_Bell_Tolls\" title=\"For Whom the Bell Tolls\">For Whom the Bell Tolls</a></i>, <a href=\"/wiki/Ernest_Hemingway\" title=\"Ernest Hemingway\">Ernest Hemingway</a></cite></div>\n</blockquote>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Origins\">Origins</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Verb_displacement&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Origins\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The term as it relates to prose in literature (as opposed to poetry or linguistics<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>) was first introduced in 2011 by <a href=\"/wiki/Tom_Heehler\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Tom Heehler\">Tom Heehler</a>, author of <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Well-Spoken_Thesaurus\" title=\"The Well-Spoken Thesaurus\">The Well-Spoken Thesaurus</a></i>, to describe one of the ways in which minimalist writers are able\u2014consciously or otherwise\u2014to enhance simple language without increasing complexity.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Verb_displacement&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/Minimalism#Literary_minimalism\" title=\"Minimalism\">Literary Minimalism</a>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Verb_displacement&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\"<a href=\"/wiki/The_Well-Spoken_Thesaurus\" title=\"The Well-Spoken Thesaurus\">The Well-Spoken Thesaurus</a>\", Tom Heehler, <a href=\"/wiki/Sourcebooks\" title=\"Sourcebooks\">Sourcebooks</a> 2011</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\"New Horizons in the Study of Language\", Noam Chomsky</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\"Language and Mind\", Noam Chomsky</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1250\nCached time: 20180901131503\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.040 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.061 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 208/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 1288/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 485/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 1169/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.007/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 802 KB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   50.028      1 -total\n 78.25%   39.149      1 Template:Quotation\n 47.52%   23.775      1 Template:Comma_separated_entries\n 19.35%    9.681      1 Template:Reflist\n 11.14%    5.574      3 Template:If_empty\n  6.58%    3.293      4 Template:Br\n  3.66%    1.831      1 Template:Main_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:31896902-0!canonical and timestamp 20180901131503 and revision id 741154768\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[],"categories":[{"sortkey":"","*":"Literature"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Minimalism"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Literary_terminology"}],"links":[{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Ernest Hemingway"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"For Whom the Bell Tolls"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Minimalism"},{"ns":0,"exi